Date: Fri, 3 Jul 2026 20:44:41 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] docs: sync live agent-skills docs with the actual Phase 0-6
 architecture

The .agents/skills.md master index points agents at docs/state-contracts.md,
docs/api-contracts.md, and docs/ui-specs/*.md as authoritative -- all three
were stale, in some cases describing endpoints/UI that never existed even
before this cleanup:

- state-contracts.md: didn't mention coreStore/Zustand as the entity-data
  source of truth at all -- described 'React Context' as if it were the
  main state model. Rewritten to match reality and point to
  docs/architecture/data-ownership.md.
- api-contracts.md: Section 3 told agents to use 'fetch or axios' directly,
  which now directly contradicts the new apiClient-only ESLint rule.
  Section 5 documented GET /api/taxonomy/graph/:configId, POST
  /api/taxonomy/map, DELETE /api/taxonomy/map/:nodeId -- none of which
  ever existed in the codebase (the real, now-removed route was
  GET /api/graph/solution/:ucid). Replaced with accurate documentation of
  the client-side graph derivation, the catalog pass-through fix, and
  streamJob's real polling. Restored /api/taxonomy/rules documentation
  (still real, unrelated to the graph node CRUD that got removed -- almost
  lost this in the section rewrite, caught and fixed before committing).
  Flagged the still-unresolved snapshotHandlers.ts vs server.ts collision
  (found during Phase 3b scoping, not yet fixed) so it isn't lost.
- ui-specs/taxonomy-graph-skills.md: claimed a 'Config Context Dropdown'
  exists. It doesn't -- confirmed by grep before editing. TaxonomyGraphView
  has the state for it (selectedConfigId) but nothing wired to change it.
  Documented as a known gap instead of a phantom feature.
- .agents/skills.md: test count was stale (311 -> 401, and noted not to
  treat the number as load-bearing); added pointers to the new
  data-ownership.md and data-architecture-plan.md; added dev reminders for
  the two new enforced rules (no direct fetch, no direct mockdata imports)
  and a note that 'npm run lint' means tsc AND eslint, not just tsc --
  a real eslint error sat in this codebase across several change sets in
  this same effort because only tsc was being checked.

No code changes in this commit -- documentation accuracy only, so what
Antigravity reads matches what actually got built.
